# Deploy Real-Time Face Detection to Render

## Overview
Deploy the 3-service system (Backend FastAPI, Frontend React, PostgreSQL) to Render.com using their free/paid tier services. The backend uses UltraFace ONNX for face detection (no dlib/OpenCV), SQLite locally and PostgreSQL in production.

---

## Key Observations

- ✅ **No dlib/OpenCV** — uses `onnxruntime` + ONNX model. Easy to build on Render.
- ✅ **Database is already flexible** — `database.py` reads `DATABASE_URL` env var; defaults to SQLite, upgrades to PostgreSQL automatically.
- ✅ **ONNX model** is downloaded at build time via `download_model.py`.
- ⚠️ **`requirements.txt` is missing `onnxruntime`** — needs to be added.
- ⚠️ **Frontend URL config** — App.jsx uses `isLocalhost` to pick backend URLs; needs Render backend URL for production.
- ⚠️ **WebSocket on Render** — Render supports WebSockets natively on Web Services.
- ⚠️ **MJPEG streaming** — Render's free tier has a 30s request timeout. The MJPEG stream is a long-lived HTTP response, which may time out. We'll add a note about this.

---

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Render Account Required**: You need a free account at [render.com](https://render.com). Sign in with your GitHub account so it can see the `Arjit2716/Real-Time-Detection-System` repo.

> [!WARNING]
> **MJPEG Streaming on Free Tier**: Render's free tier enforces a 30-second response timeout. The MJPEG `/feed/stream` endpoint is a never-ending HTTP response. This works fine on Render's **paid** tier (no timeout). On the **free** tier, the stream will be cut off every 30 seconds. The frontend will auto-reconnect, so it still works but with brief interruptions.

> [!WARNING]
> **Free Tier Sleep**: Render free Web Services spin down after 15 minutes of inactivity. The first request after sleep takes ~30 seconds.

